               <p>The prisoner being a native of France, had the evidence explained by an interpreter.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320517-162-person1340">
                  ANGELO 
                  BERNEDETTO VENTURA
               <interp inst="t18320517-162-person1340" type="surname" value="BERNEDETTO VENTURA"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320517-162-person1340" type="given" value="ANGELO"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320517-162-person1340" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Cirencester-place, and am a <rs id="t18320517-162-viclabel950" type="occupation">professor of music</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320517-162-victim1339 t18320517-162-viclabel950"></join>. Three or four days before the beginning of last month I became acquainted with the prisoner at the appartments of Mr. Burger, when he invited me to take a little play - he applied to me to lend him a guitar, which I did several times; at the beginning of April he asked me to lend him one for a night- he was not to pay for it; I did not want him to take it then, as I wanted to clean it, but he took it from a table; he was to return it the day afterwards - two days afterwards he invited me to go to his house in Bath-place; he came in a horse and gig; Mr. Crutz came with him; he saw a very beautiful guitar at my house, worth ten guineas- he said he wished to show it to his Baroness, as she would want to take a lesson very likely, and he invited me to go to Bath-place; I went there to tea - he gave his address "
               <persName id="t18320517-162-person1341">
                  Baron 
                  Dillon
               <interp inst="t18320517-162-person1341" type="surname" value="Dillon"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320517-162-person1341" type="given" value="Baron"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320517-162-person1341" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , No. 13, Bath-place, New-road;" I went, and took another guitar with me; he wished me to fetch my elegant guitar; two or three days afterwards I found the guitar I had first lent him at a pawnbroker's, in St. Martin's-lane, and two other instruments - the prisoner came to me that day; I told him I had found where he had pawned my instruments, and if he did not return them I would have him arrested; he then gave me up the duplicates of these two guitars, and a harp - this is the one I first lent him.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. ADOLPHUS. Q. You teach music, and deal in musical instruments? A. Yes; he had all three of the guitars in his possession - I leat him one, and these other two were sold; I had not sold him the three, to he paid for in three months; I had not asked him to return the one I left him - I went to a great many pawnbrokers, because I suspected I had got with a set of swindlers; I did stand once where the prisoner now does, but I went out with very great honour; you scolded my wife very much - I was charged with bigamy.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320517-162-person1342">
                  WILLIAM 
                  WILLIAMS
               <interp inst="t18320517-162-person1342" type="surname" value="WILLIAMS"></interp>
